content:
continuing on this thread
using this as a quick and dirty benchmark (it has flaws, but bear with me)
```    function warm_me_up(
        uint iterations
    )
        external
        view
        returns (uint256)
    {
        uint256 ret;
        for (uint i = 0; i < iterations; i += 1) {
            ret += i;
            ret *= i;
            ret |= (i);
            ret = addmod(ret, i, 0xffffffffffffffffff);
            ret = mulmod(ret, i, 0xffffffffffffffffff);
        }
        return ret;
    }
```
with stock client, and  I can do ~50k iterations in ~150ms (this is obviously hw dependant) with entire block's worth of gas (15M)

with  W{base,verylow,low,mid,high} reduced to 1, I can do ~160k iterations (this is not important) in ~550ms (this is important). **I can use up entire block's gas with cpu-only operations in only 0.5s. **. With blocks generated every 10s this doesn't seem too big of a deal?

I'm not saying eth will become better if we charge almost nothing for all CPU-only opcodes, only trying to understand the rationale behind different costs of CPU-only operations (in a world where real CPU utilization seems to be coming from other sources like state management).
